s to acting, and suggests ways that behavior on the screen can be linked to the presentation of self in society.Naremore's discussion of such figures as Lillian Gish, Marlene Dietrich, James Cagney, and Cary Grant will interest the specialist and the general reader alike, helping to establish standards and methods for future writing about performers and their craft.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aacting.  aactor.  acinema studies.  acinema.  acinematic history.  acinematic.  afamous actors.  afilm acting.  afilm actor.  afilm analysis.  afilm history.  afilm studies.  ahistory of film.  aideological.  aideology.  aindustrial.  amorals.  amovie theatre.  amovies.  aold hollywood.  aperformance.  ascholarly.  ascreen.  astage.  atechnology.  atheatre.  atheatrical.  auniversity.  awriting about film.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091066940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520910669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520910669/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY